Now, we need to show that the symmetric difference of A and B is not commutative with respect to intersection. Commutativity means that the order of the operation does not matter. In this case, we need to show that the symmetric difference of A and B does not equal the intersection of B and A.

Symmetric difference of A and B = {1, 2, 3, 6, 7, 8}
Intersection of B and A = {4}

Since the symmetric difference of A and B does not equal the intersection of B and A, we can conclude that the symmetric difference of A and B is not commutative with respect to intersection.
